In article <CC7nwq.Bno@festival.ed.ac.uk> richard@castle.ed.ac.uk (Richard Tobin) writes:

>Doesn't this algorithm require B to verify that p and q are indeed
>prime?  Suppose pq=75, A can tell B that the factorization is 15x5
>(15 = 3 mod 4 is bigger) or 25x3 (25 = 1 mod 4 is bigger).
>
>Is this not a problem?

B can check that the factors given to him are (with high probability)
prime. I should think it is difficult to find integers a,b,c such that 
both a*b and a*c pass the primality tests, but this is just a gut feeling.

